s one of Fowke's most prolific singers, as she collected and recorded over 120 of his songs, 66 of them transcribed for this collection. The songs, mostly of Irish origin, were popular among settlers to the Ottawa valley and in the lumber camps of northern Ontario in the late 1800s. Born in England in 1872, Abbott worked throughout Ontario and Quebec in lumber camps before settling in Hull, Quebec. He recorded numerous records for the Folkways label and performed with such folk heroes as The Travellers, Ian and Sylvia, and Pete Seeger. Songs of the North Woods as sung by O.J. Abbott and collected by Edith Fowke includes a detailed musical analysis that outlines the meter, scale, and range of each song, an index that indicates where each song can be found on the original source tapes, and extensive field notes, interviews, and recording details.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFolk songs, EnglishzOttawa River Valley (Québec and Ont.). 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Folk & Traditional.2bisacsh1 aAbbott, O. J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFowke, Edith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFowke, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLanagapka, Jeanette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLois Choksy, DFA, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPanagapka, Jeanette, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781552384527?locatt=